04190nam a22007215i 9789048553303DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485533037 a10.1515/97890485533032doi  a(DE-B1597)611919  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aQL406.5 7aART0150902bisacsh04a5942231 aGrasskamp, Anna, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aArt and Ocean Objects of Early Modern Eurasia :bShells, Bodies, and Materiality /cAnna Grasskamp. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (220 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aConnected Histories in the Early Modern World ;v400tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction -- t1 Shell Connections: The Exoticization and Eroticization of Asian Maritime Material Culture -- t2 Shell Bodies: The Creative Agency of Molluscs across Cultures -- t3 Shell Worlds: Maritime Microcosms in EurAsian Art and Material Culture -- t4 Woman with a Shell: Transcultural Exchange, Female Bodies and Maritime Matters -- tConclusion -- tCited Primary and Secondary Sources -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the early modern period, objects of maritime material culture were removed from their places of origin and traded, collected and displayed worldwide. Focusing on shells and pearls exchanged within local and global networks, this monograph compares and connects Asian, in particular Chinese, and European practices of oceanic exploitation in the framework of a transcultural history of art with an understanding of maritime material culture as gendered. Perceiving the ocean as mother of all things, as womb and birthplace, Chinese and European artists and collectors exoticized and eroticized shells’ shapes and surfaces. Defining China and Europe as spaces entangled with South and Southeast Asian sites of knowledge production, source and supply between 1500 and 1700, the book understands oceanic goods and maritime networks as transcending and subverting territorial and topographical boundaries. It also links the study of globally connected port cities to local ecologies of oceanic exploitation and creative practices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMaterial culturezEurasia. 0aShellsxCollection and preservationzChinaxHistory. 0aShellsxCollection and preservationzEuropexHistory. 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aEast Asia and North East Asia. 4aGender and Sexuality Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 7aART / History / Baroque & Rococo.2bisacsh  aMaterial culture, art, ecology, early modern period, Eurasia.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2021 Part 2z978311074335740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978904855330340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048553303423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048553303/original  a978-3-11-074335-7  DG Plus PP Package 2021 Part 2b2021  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK